<header class="hero">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="eyebrow">The rebuttals</div>
    <h1>Everything they'll say — and <span>how to answer it</span>.</h1>
    <p class="deck">
      Take this into the room. Every objection you will hear, with the answer and the source.
      Where they have a real point, I say so — because pretending otherwise is how you lose.
    </p>
  </div>
</header>

<main class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">

    <!-- 1 -->
    <div class="obj">
      <div class="claim">
        <div class="lab">They say</div>
        <h3>"Permanent affordability will chill investment. Developers won't build if they can never exit."</h3>
      </div>
      <div class="ans">
        <div class="lab">You say</div>
        <p>
          This is an empirical claim, and it has been tested. <strong>Vermont requires affordability
          in perpetuity, and has since the early 2000s.</strong>
        </p>
        <p>
          The result was not a developer strike. Vermont gets <strong>two to three times more demand
          for tax credits than it has credits to award</strong>, with a waiting list.
        </p>
        <p>
          And Vermont is not alone in going far past the federal minimum. Oregon requires 60 years.
          California, 55. Massachusetts, Montana and Utah, 50. The average state term is about 42
          years. Developers keep building in all of them.
        </p>
        <div class="kill">
          They have been running this experiment for twenty years and it produced the opposite of
          what you're predicting. Why should New York be different?
        </div>
        <div class="cite">Sources: Shelterforce; National Housing Trust analysis of state Qualified Allocation Plans.</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- 2 -->
    <div class="obj">
      <div class="claim">
        <div class="lab">They say</div>
        <h3>"Most LIHTC units stay affordable after the restrictions expire anyway. Freddie Mac found it."</h3>
      </div>
      <div class="ans">
        <div class="lab">You say</div>
        <p>
          Read their caveats, because Freddie Mac wrote them down. <strong>They warn that severe rent
          hikes remain likely for deeply-targeted units</strong> — the ones affordable at 30% of AMI —
          because the gap between those rents and market rents is enormous in nearly any submarket.
          <strong>Over half of LIHTC tenants earn below 30% of AMI.</strong>
        </p>
        <p>
          Their sample was <strong>134 properties across seven metro areas</strong>. And they were
          <strong>unable to establish a clear statistical relationship between local market
          conditions and whether a property exits</strong>.
        </p>
        <p>
          That is not evidence that hot markets don't drive conversions. It is an admission that
          their data couldn't tell.
        </p>
        <div class="kill">
          A national average of "mostly fine" is meaningless in a building where the restricted rent
          is $1,200 and the market rent is $6,000. Averages don't get evicted. People do.
        </div>
        <div class="cite">Source: Freddie Mac, <em>LIHTC at Risk</em>; summarised by the National Low Income Housing Coalition.</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- 3 -->
    <div class="obj">
      <div class="claim">
        <div class="lab">They say</div>
        <h3>"The real problem is supply. We just need to build more housing."</h3>
      </div>
      <div class="ans">
        <div class="lab">You say</div>
        <p>
          Build. I'm not against building. But look at <em>where</em> the shortage actually is.
        </p>
        <p>
          New York's overall rental vacancy rate is 1.41%. But for apartments under $1,100 a month
          it is <strong>0.39%</strong>. For apartments at $2,400 and above it is <strong>3.39%</strong>.
          The apartments are not missing. <strong>The cheap apartments are missing.</strong>
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>703,628 households need rents below $1,100. There were 2,297 such apartments
          vacant and available.</strong> Meanwhile the median asking rent on new listings is $3,500
          or more.
        </p>
        <div class="kill">
          You cannot build your way out of a 0.39% vacancy rate at $1,100 by adding apartments at
          $3,500. And every year we lose the ones we already have, we build backwards.
        </div>
        <div class="cite">Sources: NYC Housing &amp; Vacancy Survey 2023; ANHD.</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- 4 -->
    <div class="obj">
      <div class="claim">
        <div class="lab">They say</div>
        <h3>"Preservation is too expensive. We can't afford to buy every expiring building."</h3>
      </div>
      <div class="ans">
        <div class="lab">You say</div>
        <p>
          Preserving a home is <strong>consistently cheaper than building a new one</strong>. The
          building is already standing. There is no land to acquire, no years of financing delay, no
          construction timeline.
        </p>
        <p>
          But do the other half of the arithmetic, because nobody ever does. <strong>Win — the
          largest provider of transitional housing for families with children in this city — puts
          the cost of homelessness at roughly $18,900 per person, per year.</strong>
        </p>
        <p>
          My building has seventy apartments. Suppose only a fifth of those households end up in
          shelter — say twenty families, fifty people. That is <strong>close to a million dollars a
          year</strong>. Not once. <em>Every year, for as long as they're in there.</em> And at the
          end of it the city owns nothing, and the families have nothing.
        </p>
        <p>
          Meanwhile the city's acquisition and rehab fund was relaunched in April 2025
          <strong>capitalised at $13 million</strong> — less than the asking price of a single
          Brooklyn apartment building.
        </p>
        <div class="kill">
          You are not choosing between spending money and not spending money.
          You are choosing between spending it <em>once</em>, on a building — or
          <em>forever</em>, on shelter, and having nothing to show for it.
        </div>
        <div class="cite">Sources: Win, cost of homelessness per person per year; NYC acquisition fund capitalisation, April 2025. <a href="/who-paid/" style="color:var(--navy)">The full accounting →</a></div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- 5 -->
    <div class="obj">
      <div class="claim">
        <div class="lab">They say</div>
        <h3>"The landlord kept his side of the deal. Thirty years was the agreement. He's entitled to his return."</h3>
      </div>
      <div class="ans">
        <div class="lab">You say</div>
        <p>
          He is. I'm not against landlords making money on their investments, and I've never said I was.
        </p>
        <p>
          But be precise about what the deal actually delivered. My building was bought at a
          foreclosure auction for about <strong>$4 million</strong> — roughly $57,000 a unit —
          because nobody wanted to live here. <strong>I have personally paid my current landlord
          roughly two and a half times what he paid for my apartment.</strong> Multiply by seventy.
        </p>
        <p>
          And the reason the building is now worth a fortune is that seventy working-class families
          spent thirty years turning a place you couldn't walk around at night into a place everyone
          wants to live. <strong>We didn't watch the appreciation happen. We caused it.</strong>
        </p>
        <div class="kill">
          The public subsidised the building. The tenants paid the mortgage. The tenants made the
          neighbourhood valuable. And all three of those facts are now the reason we're told we
          can't afford to stay.
        </div>
        <div class="cite">The $4m foreclosure sale was reported in the <em>New York Times</em>. <a href="/who-paid/" style="color:var(--navy)">The full accounting →</a></div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- 6 -->
    <div class="obj">
      <div class="claim">
        <div class="lab">They say</div>
        <h3>"Expiration isn't eviction. Tenants have Good Cause protections now."</h3>
      </div>
      <div class="ans">
        <div class="lab">You say</div>
        <p>
          Good Cause is real and it matters — and it is not a substitute for affordability.
        </p>
        <p>
          It has exemptions, and the exemptions are exactly where subsidised buildings tend to fall:
          condominium status, existing rent regulation, small-owner carve-outs. In my own building,
          the landlord argued we weren't covered <em>because he had classified the building as a
          condominium</em> — a building that has never operated as one, and never sold a single unit.
        </p>
        <p>
          A protection you have to litigate is not a protection you have. And Good Cause does nothing
          at all for the next tenant, or for the unit, or for the affordable housing stock. It slows
          the loss. It does not prevent it.
        </p>
        <div class="kill">
          "You can stay, but the apartment is gone when you die" is not an affordable housing policy.
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- 7 -->
    <div class="obj">
      <div class="claim">
        <div class="lab">They say</div>
        <h3>"This is a federal programme. There's nothing New York can do."</h3>
      </div>
      <div class="ans">
        <div class="lab">You say</div>
        <p>
          That is simply not true, and every housing agency in the state knows it.
        </p>
        <p>
          The 30-year term is a <strong>federal minimum</strong>. Each state writes its own
          <strong>Qualified Allocation Plan</strong> — the rulebook for how it awards the credits —
          and can require more. More than three dozen states already require or incentivise longer
          terms than the federal floor. That is where Vermont's perpetual affordability comes from.
          That is where Oregon's sixty years comes from.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>New York chooses the minimum.</strong> Nobody in Washington made us do that, and
          changing it does not require a single dollar or a single vote from Congress.
        </p>
        <div class="kill">
          This is not a federal problem we're stuck with. It's a state choice we keep making.
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- 8 -->
    <div class="obj">
      <div class="claim">
        <div class="lab">They say</div>
        <h3>"Nobody could have foreseen this. It's just an unfortunate outcome of an old programme."</h3>
      </div>
      <div class="ans">
        <div class="lab">You say</div>
        <p>
          It was foreseeable by anyone who did arithmetic. The term was written as thirty years. The
          people moving in were in their thirties, forties and fifties. Nobody needed a crystal ball
          to work out that most of them would still be alive and still need somewhere to live.
        </p>
        <p>
          The programme was built with an <strong>exit and no landing</strong>. Not a bad landing —
          <em>no landing</em>. There is no provision to consult when the term ends, no agency with a
          duty to act, no process for the families inside.
        </p>
        <p>
          The industry calls it a <strong>sunset</strong>. That word was chosen by people for whom
          the end of the term was an administrative milestone. For the person still living in the
          apartment, it is <strong>doomsday</strong>.
        </p>
        <div class="kill">
          The thirty-year term is a bet that tenants won't be there at the end.
          Most of them are.
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- HONEST -->
    <h2 style="margin-top:56px">Where they have a point</h2>
    <p class="lead">
      Do not walk into a room pretending the other side has no case. You will get taken apart, and
      you will deserve it. Here is what's true, and how to hold it and still win.
    </p>

    <div class="honest">
      <h3>Some buildings really are in financial distress.</h3>
      <p>
        Operating costs — insurance, fuel, labour, maintenance — have risen sharply, and there is a
        genuine subset of regulated and subsidised buildings where the numbers do not work. Nonprofit
        owners are struggling too, not just predatory ones. If you deny this, you sound like you've
        never read a building's books.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>How to hold it:</strong> agree, and then insist on the distinction. Distress is an
        argument for <em>subsidy and support</em> — for operating assistance, for insurance relief,
        for capital funding. It is not an argument for <em>letting affordability expire</em>. Those
        are different problems with different solutions, and the industry deliberately blurs them.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="honest">
      <h3>LIHTC has genuinely built millions of homes.</h3>
      <p>
        It is the largest source of affordable housing finance in the country, and in most places
        the only one. It housed me for thirty years at a rent I could pay. Attacking it as a failure
        full stop is both unfair and strategically stupid — it makes you sound like you'd rather have
        nothing.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>How to hold it:</strong> say the true thing. <em>LIHTC works, right up until the
        moment it stops — and nobody wrote down what happens then.</em> We are not asking to abolish
        it. We are asking to fix the ending.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="honest">
      <h3>Permanent affordability costs more up front.</h3>
      <p>
        A longer or perpetual term does change the deal economics. Vermont proves developers still
        show up — but it is not free, and if you claim it is, someone with a spreadsheet will
        embarrass you.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>How to hold it:</strong> concede the cost, then compare it to the alternative. We
        currently pay for thirty years of affordability <em>and then buy the building back at market
        rate</em> — or lose it, and pay to shelter the people who were in it. Paying once is cheaper
        than paying twice.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="pull" style="margin-top:44px">
      The strongest position in the room is the one that has already conceded
      everything true the other side is going to say.
    </div>

  </div>
</main>

